On the whole, however, there can be little doubt but thot his work may be accepted as that of a sagacious thinker and painstaking inquiror. He , has contrivcd to compress into a small compass much really valuable matter, and has enabled us to perceive in their earliest workings the germs of certain medi· . eval and modern institutione. It would be too much to suppose that he was guided to this result by a deli· berate and consciens foresight‚ or that he ever so dimly anticipated from what most impressed him with admiration in the character of these tribes, the esta- blishment of a new world on the ruine of the Romen empire. Tacitus, we believe, was far too deeply im- bned with Roman ideas to admit such a notion into hie mind. He was no doubt struck with the eontrast presented by the domestic virtues of the Germane to- the corruption and profligacy of his countrymen, and he continually avails himself of it to point the satire of which he was so great a master. He felt, too, as is evident from the ominous language at the close ol ch. 33, that there was danger to the empire from the side of Germany. But neither was his admiration of the Germane by any means unqualified, as is clearly shown by his exposurc of their vices, nor is there any- thing to imply that he feared the worst for his coun- try. On the contrary, the auspicious opening of Nerva's reign, and the increasing strength and pros- perity of the empire under Trajan, seem to have in· spired him with new saith in the ,destinies of Rome.
